args: I will never forget the night I first left\nthe Faerie Kingdom.
I was so skittish, I took a couple of steps\ninto the surrounding forest and...stopped.
*sniff* Well, great. Now I've dallied\nso long that night has fallen.
(It would be dangerous to set out in search\nof a town now, so perhaps it's best to find\na safe spot to bed down for the evening.)
Oh, it's just a bunny... Your cottony tush\nnearly gave me heart failure, Mr. Bunny!
(Oh, but I hate this. Why DO we have this\nstupid tradition of going out into the\nhuman world, anyway?)
(I can't do this; I lack both the bravery\nand talent of my siblings.)
(I'm just the timid baby of the family,\nand I'm going to end the night in some\nforest critter's stomach!)
I've barely ever left the palace,\nlet alone the kingdom. It's hopeless!
Is that a baby? But why would...?
(Why is there a baby crying\nin the woods at night?)
Then the baby I heard is your daughter?\nWho has done this thing to you?!
She's not breathing... No!\nThis can't be happening!
Not yet, but I know she's in these woods!
I've got to get out of here!
That light... Is it dawn already?
(It seems her foul pursuers have\ngiven up the chase.)
I guess they didn't expect a baby\nto fly off into the treetops.
Oh! I'm sorry, little one!\nI didn't mean to wake you.
Oh dear. What's wrong? Are you hungry?
What do human babies even eat?\nWas that woman your mother?\nWhere is your father?
(This child is even weaker than I am; she\nwon't live out the day if I abandon her.)
(I may not be special—and I may be a\ncoward—but I have to get it together.)
Easy there, little Ilia. I've got you.
I traveled from town to town in search of\nher father, but he never turned up, so—
Er, might we back up a moment?\nThis is rather a lot to process.
If I may, how old ARE you, Meene?\nYou don't seem much older than myself.
Hee hee! That's a secret. But I'll let you\nknow that we faeries live much longer\nlives than your kind—and look younger.
I suppose so. Now then, did I mishear,\nor did you say you lived in a palace?
The youngest of thirteen, though. Oh,\nand we hide our status while out in the\nworld, so it doesn't confer any perks.
The whole point of our time in the human\nrealm is to learn more about the world\nwithout the benefit of status.
Now, I certainly didn't mean to spend my\ntime there raising a child, but I'm still\nvery glad that I met Ilia.
To be honest, I'd always felt inferior to my\nolder siblings; I was weak, shy, and so\nterribly afraid of everything.
But raising her changed all that,\nand I rather like the faerie I've become.
A love that crosses the bounds of race...
Indeed. In these days, humans and\ndragons are locked in war, and we faeries\nhave taken the side of the dragons.
The origins of our kind lie with them,\nafter all, and we still share a deep bond.
I remember hearing that dragons and\nfaeries were distant relatives.
That's right. So, strictly speaking, faeries\nand humankind should be enemies.
But my love for Ilia makes all that\nquite meaningless.
It is unshakable—and it always will be.
